In article <1993May26.015744.6366@usage.csd.unsw.OZ.AU> chuck@cse.unsw.edu.au (Mark Andrew Hawling) writes:
>	 Seems to be some form of code that C= used in their
>1.3 WB. Any hints on what it is, why does everybody hate it, and how much
>is left in the new OS's ? Oh I am talking about BCPL ... is it that what it's
>called ?

BCPL is a programming language. 
Back in the beginning of Amiga MEtacomco ported Tripos to the amiga
and eventually became AmigaDos. Trips was written in BCPL. 
Until 36.xx dos.library was still using BCPL code, as a lot of 
commands in the c: directory. 

Why 'does everybody hate it?' 
Because BCPL has BPtr (BCPL-Pointers) that behave differently than 
Amiga APtr. (BCPL pointer points to the natural unit in a 32 bit
enviroment, APtr point to the smallest addressable unit of 8 bit)
Writing and reading Dos structures is a pain, because you have to convert 
from one pointer type to the other. Similar you have to convert strings.

Hope this helps
