In article <C77zAr.2IL@news.iastate.edu> barrett@iastate.edu (Marc N. Barrett) writes:

>   I see an awful lot of bashing of AmigaBASIC.  

And for good reason.  Nonetheless, it was an improvement over ABasiC at the
time.  And there are something like 6-8 commercial BASICs for the Amiga
these days, not to mention the FR stuff.  Had AmigaBASIC followed the Amiga
guidelines and provided a better environment, few would have needed to look
elsewhere.  As it stands, the AmigaBASIC language isn't that bad given the
timeframe.  AMOS Basic doesn't quite match it in language features, though
of course it provides zillions more functions and a better environment.  Only
F-Basic and Blitz Basic provide significant language enhancements (primarily
RECORDs/STRUCTures were missing from Amiga BASIC).

>AmigaOS 1.2 was junk mostly (the 'look' was utterly pathetic), GraphiCraft 
>was junk, TextCraft was junk, MusiCraft was junk, etc...  All of these were 
>written by Commodore, so there are no excuses.

GraphicCraft was hastily written after the contracted deal for a graphic 
program fell through.  The other "Craft" programs, just like AmigaBASIC, 
were contracted.  And actually, GraphicCraft's main flaw was lack of features, 
it didn't have quite the "ignore the OS" problems many of these others
had (hell, TextCraft didn't even run on the 68010).  Certainly C= is to
blame for accepting substandard programs, but they're not to blame for
writing them.
