chbeck@anl.gov (Chuck Beck) writes:

>The original Amiga was simply a game machine, based on a fantastic
>custom chipset.

Nope.  The original Amiga was a full-fledged computer.  I've got the
docs, I can prove it :-)

>C= bought the failing company before it could release any
>products, except a joystick, and they gave the company a huge influx of
>cash, and decided that the game machine market was getting stale, so C=
>turned development toward making a fantastic computer instead.

Nope.  Amiga did sell joysticks (and joyboards), but that was to raise
money for development.  Commodore bought a *computer*, not a game machine.

>They added
>all the computer ports, (serial, parallel, floppy, better video etc) and
>came up with the multitasking OS. 

Nope.  All of that existed in the original Amiga Lorraine.  The only thing
added by Commodore was the DOS portion of the AmigaOS, and that only because
Amiga's DOS wasn't anywhere near finished, and they wanted to release a
machine quickly, so C= contracted with an English group to do a port of
TRIPOS, an existing OS/DOS.  But that TRIPOS port was reworked specifically
to interact with the already existing Exec - which was pretty much identical
to the Exec we all know and love now.  Intuition, as well, was a product
of Amiga, not of Commodore.  And the only changes C= made to the hardware
were to change from a 5-1/4" floppy to a 3-1/2" floppy, and to remove the
"cartridge" port - which was actually a much more general-purpose expansion
port, designed to allow add-on processors, such as MS-DOS "cartridges" with
an 8088 on-board.  They also did some cleanup and redesign, but didn't
change any of the basic functionality.

>I have a cassette of RJ Micall's talk several years ago at one of the
>computer fests up here that is very enlightening on the history of 
>the Amiga.

Well, you don't seem to have *listened* to it, as your "history" is very
close to being completely bogus.  And for information's sake, here's
my qualifications to say that: I was there, sort of.  I'd been working
with a company that was talking to Amiga about producing some killer
demos for the new machine (that's how I got the old docs).  Also, I'd
done some consulting work with Rob Peck, one of the original Amiga dudez
(sadly, now deceased), and we'd talked about the fantastic new machine
quite a bit.

