Apple spent lots of marketing money selling the Apple II systems into
"professional" applications back in the 70s.  Due these good ads, and
the lack of much organized competition, they were regarded as a
professional system.  Most other 6502 based systems, like the C64,
were marketed as game machines and home computers.  Apple did a few
technical things right, like offering a few slots in the Apple II.
But it was mainly marketing; the C64 was in many ways a more powerful
system.  

IBM would have been regarded as professional no matter what they
entered the market with at the time.  It just happened that, since
they didn't really understand the PC market, they copied lots of
stuff.  The Apple II, the largest single success in the business
market at the time, had slots, so they would too.  And CP/M was a
pretty big success as a business OS, though on many machines with no
big company leading.  MS-DOS began as a bad clone of CP/M, but it was
close enough for CP/M users to be comfortable using.  It was IBM's
past reputation, and good marketing once again, that sold the business
community on the IBM PC.  Macs took a long time to establish in much
of any business market, and Apple hasn't been all that happy getting
them into as much of that market as they want.  Yet, good marketing
and past reputation is responsible for the Mac's success.

Rule # 1: The average PC user is afraid of computers and of change.
Rule # 2: Technical merit is meaningless to the masses.
Rule # 3: Belief is more important than reality.

These rules actually function circularly to explain a whole lot about
the past 10-15 years of the computer industry.  Why it didn't matter
how bad the 80x86 architecture was.  Why MS-DOS and MS-Windows were
