Just try to explain that to a biologist, he'll laugh in your face.

>Go ahead, ask a few people you know what a clone is; I 
>guarantee you that 99% of them will tell you that they're IBM clones!

Now pretend you have a life, and ask a few non-computer-centered people you
know.  The results will be considerably different.  But enough of such
nonsense...

>Besides, why the hell would anyone want to build an Amiga clone? In case 
>you haven't noticed, the Amiga wasn't selling; that's why C= went down! 

You don't have the first clue why Commodore went down.  It was entirely due
to management incompentance, it had nothing to do with Amiga sales.  Except
for the fact that, through mismanagement, Commodore lost money and go to the
point where they couldn't afford the parts to meet the demand for Amigas.
Or, for that matter, the cost of maintaining the once-huge Commodore
infrastructure.

That's not to say that Amiga clones would be guaranteed a success, or would
replace the PClones anytime soon.  But it's certainly possible, especially
in their existing areas of strength, that Amiga clones would do quite well
if marketed by companies who actually had a clue.

>And furthermore I guarantee, all the advertising in the world will not 
>change this anymore; Microsoft's grip is WAY TOO tight! Guess why 
>INTELLIGENT companies like Silicon Graphics, etc. don't chose to enter 
>their systems in the home market--they'd lose BIG TIME, unless they made 
>them MS compatible!

Silicon Graphics in entering the home market in a big way -- they're
teaming with Nintendo to deliver a super game machine based around bits of
their workstation architecture.  Sure, you can't directly compete with the
home PClone "Hey, I can take all the software I get at work and use it at
home and trade with my friends, etc." market.  But an entry level Windows
box is still over twice the price of an entry level Amiga.  

That's not to mention "niche" markets.  There are plenty of places to use
computers that aren't being served by the existing players, often due to the
inexplicable bloat of the MS-Windows operating system, other times due to
basic failings in the MS-Windows or PC-Clone architectures.
