No, not the OS, just the user interface, and yes, it *IS* 30 years
old.  If computer scientists were more interested in innovating
instead of copying, the mouse-and-menu stuff should have been
improved on, and moved-past *decades* ago, but there's no incentive
[and indeed, no financial payoff] to do that when just copying is
so much easier and cheaper [and less risky].

I don't remember what system he started on.  At some point he was
working on a TENEX system and his setup was *beaucoup* expensive.
[recall that the _hardware_ didn't really exist yet for the kind of
bitmapped displays we use now, and so he had to use VERY expensive stuff
to do his drawing; moreover, there was essentially no hardware assist on
the PDP-10 and so it was _very_ CPU intensive.  Basically, just a few
NLS users could bring a pretty big timesharing system to its knees].

While I have little but scorn for the software engineers who feel
all proud at their ability to copy-copy-copy [for *thirty*years*],
I'm awstruck at the advances the _hardware_ world has made in the
transformation for what it took to do all that "back then" versus
what can do it easily now.

